(58, 1, 7, 12, 6, 17, 17, 'angels spirits, and his ministers a flame of fire', 'Angels and Fire Imagery', 'This connection highlights the imagery of angels as agents of divine action. Both passages emphasize the presence of angels and fire, with Hebrews describing angels as ''spirits'' and ''a flame of fire,'' while 2 Kings depicts a vision of ''horses and chariots of fire'' surrounding Elisha.', 'theme', 0.384, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(58, 1, 7, 12, 2, 11, 11, 'a flame of fire', 'Angelic Imagery in Scripture', 'This connection highlights the use of fire imagery associated with angels. In Hebrews, angels are described as ''spirits'' and ''a flame of fire,'' while in 2 Kings, a ''chariot of fire'' signifies divine presence.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(58, 1, 7, 26, 1, 13, 14, 'a flame of fire', 'Connection of Fire Imagery', 'Both passages emphasize the imagery of fire, with Hebrews describing angels as ''a flame of fire'' and Ezekiel depicting living creatures with ''the appearance of burning coals of fire.'' This connection highlights the dynamic and powerful nature of divine beings.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(58, 1, 7, 38, 6, 5, 5, 'angels spirits', 'Connection of Angels and Spirits', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of angels as spirits. Hebrews describes angels as ''spirits,'' while Zechariah refers to ''spirits of the heavens,'' suggesting a thematic link between the two texts.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(58, 1, 7, 27, 7, 10, 10, 'his ministers a flame of fire', 'Angels as Ministers of Fire', 'This connection highlights the role of angels as ministers, depicted in both passages. Hebrews describes angels as ''ministers a flame of fire,'' while Daniel mentions ''thousand thousands ministered unto him,'' suggesting a shared theme of angelic service and divine presence.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(58, 1, 8, 19, 45, 6, 7, 'Thy throne, O God, is for ever and ever', 'Connection of Divine Kingship', 'Both passages emphasize the eternal nature of God''s throne and the righteousness of His kingdom. The phrase ''Thy throne, O God, is for ever and ever'' appears in both, linking them thematically.', 'theme', 0.9299999999999999, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
