(58, 12, 15, 48, 5, 4, 4, 'fail of the grace of God', 'Connection of Grace and Bitterness', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of grace and warn against falling away from it. Hebrews 12:15 mentions failing of the grace of God, while Galatians 5:4 discusses falling from grace, highlighting the consequences of turning away from God''s grace.', 'theme', 0.384, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(58, 12, 15, 47, 6, 1, 1, 'grace of God', 'Grace of God Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of not failing to receive God''s grace. Hebrews warns against bitterness that can defile, while 2 Corinthians urges not to receive grace in vain.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(58, 12, 15, 63, 1, 8, 8, 'fail of the grace of God', 'Warning Against Spiritual Neglect', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of vigilance in faith. Hebrews warns against failing the grace of God, while 2 John encourages believers to look to themselves to maintain their rewards.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(58, 12, 15, 46, 15, 33, 33, 'root of bitterness', 'Corruption from Bitterness and Evil', 'This connection highlights how negative influences, such as a ''root of bitterness,'' can lead to broader moral corruption, paralleling the idea that ''evil communications corrupt good manners.'' Both passages warn against the impact of harmful influences on one''s character and community.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(58, 12, 15, 20, 4, 23, 23, 'Looking diligently', 'Diligence in Heart and Grace', 'This connection highlights the importance of diligence in both passages. Hebrews 12:15 warns against bitterness that can defile, while Proverbs 4:23 emphasizes keeping the heart diligently, as it influences life.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(58, 12, 16, 1, 25, 31, 34, 'profane person, as Esau', 'Esau''s Birthright and Profanity', 'This connection highlights Esau''s choice to sell his birthright for immediate gratification, which is described as profane in Hebrews. Both passages emphasize the value of the birthright and Esau''s disregard for it.', 'theme', 0.398, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(58, 12, 16, 46, 6, 15, 20, 'fornicator, or profane person, as Esau', 'Connection Between Fornication and Birthright', 'Both passages emphasize the consequences of valuing immediate gratification over spiritual integrity. Esau''s selling of his birthright for a meal parallels the warning against fornication, which compromises one''s body as a temple of the Holy Spirit.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(58, 12, 16, 58, 13, 4, 4, 'profane person, as Esau', 'Connection of Sexual Morality', 'Both passages emphasize the consequences of sexual immorality. Hebrews 12:16 warns against profane behavior, while Hebrews 13:4 highlights God''s judgment on whoremongers and adulterers.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(58, 12, 16, 66, 22, 15, 15, 'profane person, as Esau', 'Connection of Profanity and Immorality', 'Both passages emphasize the consequences of immoral behavior. Hebrews warns against being profane like Esau, while Revelation lists various immoral acts, including whoremongers, highlighting the seriousness of such actions.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(58, 12, 16, 41, 7, 21, 21, 'fornicator, or profane person', 'Connection of Fornication and Profanity', 'Both passages emphasize the negative consequences of immoral behavior, linking fornication and profane actions. Hebrews warns against being like Esau, while Mark lists fornication among evil thoughts from the heart.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(58, 12, 16, 44, 15, 29, 29, 'fornicator, or profane person, as Esau', 'Connection Between Fornication and Birthright', 'This connection highlights the theme of moral choices impacting one''s spiritual inheritance. Both passages emphasize the importance of abstaining from fornication and making wise decisions regarding one''s birthright.', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(58, 12, 16, 52, 4, 3, 7, 'fornicator, or profane person', 'Connection of Fornication and Holiness', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of abstaining from fornication and living in holiness. Hebrews warns against being profane like Esau, while 1 Thessalonians calls for sanctification and honor in one''s conduct.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(58, 12, 17, 20, 1, 24, 31, 'found no place of repentance', 'Rejection of Wisdom and Blessing', 'This connection highlights the consequences of rejecting wisdom and guidance. Both passages emphasize the futility of seeking repentance or help after disregarding counsel, as seen in Esau''s rejection and the refusal of wisdom.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(58, 12, 17, 40, 25, 11, 12, 'found no place of repentance', 'Rejection and Seeking Acceptance', 'This connection highlights the theme of seeking acceptance after rejection. In both passages, individuals seek to regain what they have lost, but ultimately face rejection despite their efforts.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(58, 12, 17, 40, 7, 23, 23, 'found no place of repentance', 'Rejection and Lack of Repentance', 'This connection highlights the theme of rejection in both passages. In Hebrews, the focus is on Esau''s rejection after seeking repentance, while in Matthew, the rejection is of those who are not known by Christ despite their claims.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(58, 12, 17, 58, 6, 8, 8, 'rejected', 'Rejection and Consequences', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of rejection and its dire consequences. In Hebrews 12:17, the rejection leads to a loss of blessing, while Hebrews 6:8 describes the rejection of unfruitful land, indicating a similar outcome of destruction.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(58, 12, 17, 58, 10, 26, 29, 'found no place of repentance', 'Consequences of Rejection', 'This connection highlights the severe consequences of rejecting God''s grace. Both passages emphasize the idea of being rejected after seeking repentance, illustrating the gravity of willful sin and its repercussions.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(58, 12, 17, 1, 27, 30, 41, 'found no place of repentance', 'Esau''s Loss of Blessing', 'Both passages emphasize Esau''s deep regret and sorrow after losing his blessing. Hebrews highlights that he sought repentance but found none, paralleling his bitter cry in Genesis when he pleads for a blessing.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(58, 12, 17, 24, 6, 30, 30, 'rejected', 'Rejection and Repentance Theme', 'This connection highlights the theme of rejection in both passages. Hebrews 12:17 speaks of being rejected after seeking repentance, while Jeremiah 6:30 refers to those rejected by the Lord as ''reprobate.''', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(58, 12, 18, 5, 4, 11, 11, NULL, 'Connection of Mountain Imagery', 'Both passages emphasize the mountain that burned with fire and darkness. Hebrews 12:18 reflects on the experience described in Deuteronomy 4:11, highlighting the terrifying nature of God''s presence at Sinai.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(58, 12, 18, 2, 24, 17, 17, 'that burned with fire', 'Connection of Divine Fire Imagery', 'Both passages emphasize the presence of fire associated with God''s glory. Hebrews 12:18 refers to a mountain that burned with fire, paralleling Exodus 24:17''s depiction of the Lord''s glory as devouring fire.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(58, 12, 18, 2, 20, 18, 18, 'mount that might be touched', 'Connection of Mount Imagery', 'Both passages emphasize the fearful and awe-inspiring nature of the mountain experience. Hebrews 12:18 refers to a mountain that cannot be touched, paralleling the terrifying scene described in Exodus 20:18 where the mountain is smoking and the people stand afar off.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(58, 12, 18, 5, 5, 22, 26, 'burned with fire', 'Connection of Divine Encounter', 'Both passages emphasize the dramatic encounter with God at the mountain, characterized by fire and darkness. Hebrews 12:18 contrasts this fearful experience with the new covenant, highlighting the shift from the physical to the spiritual.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(58, 12, 18, 45, 6, 14, 14, NULL, 'Connection Between Law and Grace', 'This connection highlights the transition from the fear associated with the law, as represented by the ''mount that might be touched,'' to the grace that liberates believers from sin''s dominion. Both passages emphasize a shift from a fearful, law-based relationship to one characterized by grace.', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(58, 12, 18, 47, 3, 9, 9, NULL, 'Contrast of Glory and Condemnation', 'This connection highlights the contrast between the fearful experience at Mount Sinai, described in Hebrews, and the greater glory of the new covenant ministry in 2 Corinthians. Both passages emphasize the transition from a ministry associated with condemnation to one of righteousness and glory.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(58, 12, 18, 45, 8, 15, 15, NULL, 'Connection of Fear and Adoption', 'This connection highlights the contrast between fear and the assurance of belonging. Hebrews 12:18 describes a fearful encounter with God, while Romans 8:15 emphasizes the Spirit of adoption that removes fear.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(58, 12, 19, 5, 18, 16, 16, NULL, 'Fear of God''s Voice', 'Both passages emphasize the fear of hearing God''s voice. In Hebrews, the people requested not to hear the voice any more, mirroring the plea in Deuteronomy for the same reason of fear.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(58, 12, 19, 46, 15, 52, 52, 'the sound of a trumpet', 'Connection of Trumpet Imagery', 'This connection highlights the significance of the trumpet in both passages. Hebrews 12:19 mentions ''the sound of a trumpet,'' while 1 Corinthians 15:52 speaks of ''the last trump,'' emphasizing the role of the trumpet in divine communication and transformation.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(58, 12, 19, 2, 20, 1, 19, 'the sound of a trumpet', 'Connection of Divine Communication', 'Both passages emphasize the dramatic nature of God''s communication with His people, particularly through the sound of a trumpet and the fear it instills. The fear expressed in Hebrews 12:19 reflects the response of the people in Exodus 20:19, who requested Moses to speak on their behalf due to their fear of God''s voice.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(58, 12, 19, 5, 4, 12, 12, 'the voice of words', 'Connection of Divine Communication', 'Both passages emphasize the auditory experience of God''s voice. Hebrews 12:19 mentions ''the voice of words,'' paralleling Deuteronomy 4:12''s reference to ''the voice of the words.'' This connection highlights the significance of hearing God''s communication without visual representation.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(58, 12, 19, 2, 20, 22, 22, 'the voice of words', 'Divine Communication and Fear', 'Both passages emphasize the direct communication from God to His people. The sound of a trumpet in Hebrews reflects the awe and fear experienced by the Israelites when God spoke to them from heaven in Exodus.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(58, 12, 19, 52, 4, 16, 16, 'the sound of a trumpet', 'Connection of Trumpet and Voice', 'This connection highlights the use of a trumpet and voice in both passages. Hebrews 12:19 mentions ''the sound of a trumpet'' and ''the voice of words,'' while 1 Thessalonians 4:16 refers to ''the trump of God'' and ''the voice of the archangel.''', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(58, 12, 20, 2, 19, 12, 13, NULL, 'Connection of Divine Boundaries', 'Both passages emphasize the severe consequences for touching the mountain, highlighting the holiness and danger associated with God''s presence. The command in Exodus is reiterated in Hebrews, showing a continuity in the seriousness of the divine command.', 'theme', 0.377, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(58, 12, 20, 5, 33, 2, 2, 'that which was commanded', 'Divine Presence and Law', 'Both passages emphasize the holiness of God''s presence and the seriousness of His law. Hebrews 12:20 reflects the fear surrounding God''s commands at Sinai, while Deuteronomy 33:2 describes the fiery law given from the mountain.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(58, 12, 20, 48, 2, 19, 19, 'if so much as a beast touch the mountain', 'Connection of Law and Death', 'This connection highlights the severity of the law as seen in Hebrews, where even a beast touching the mountain faces death. In Galatians, the speaker expresses being ''dead to the law,'' suggesting a similar theme of the law''s ultimate consequence.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(58, 12, 20, 48, 3, 10, 10, 'could not endure that which was commanded', 'Connection Between Law and Curse', 'Both passages emphasize the severity of the law and its consequences. Hebrews highlights the inability to endure the law''s commands, while Galatians states that those under the law are cursed if they do not follow it completely.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(58, 12, 20, 45, 3, 19, 20, 'they could not endure that which was commanded', 'Connection of Law and Guilt', 'This connection highlights the severity of the law as seen in Hebrews, where even a beast touching the mountain faces dire consequences. Similarly, Romans emphasizes that the law reveals guilt and does not justify anyone, underscoring the weight of the commandments.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(58, 12, 21, 2, 19, 16, 16, 'I exceedingly fear and quake', 'Fear and Trembling at Sinai', 'Both passages emphasize the fear experienced by Moses and the people at Mount Sinai. In Exodus, the people trembled due to the terrifying sights and sounds, while Hebrews reflects Moses'' own fear in response to the divine presence.', 'theme', 0.391, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(58, 12, 21, 5, 9, 19, 19, 'I exceedingly fear and quake', 'Fear of God''s Anger', 'This connection highlights the theme of fear in the presence of God''s wrath. Both passages emphasize the intense fear experienced by Moses in response to God''s anger and displeasure.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(58, 12, 21, 23, 6, 3, 5, 'I exceedingly fear and quake', 'Fear and Awe in God''s Presence', 'Both passages emphasize the overwhelming fear and awe experienced in the presence of God. Moses expresses his fear in Hebrews, while Isaiah acknowledges his unworthiness and fear after seeing the Lord.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(58, 12, 21, 19, 119, 120, 120, 'I exceedingly fear and quake', 'Fear and Trembling in Scripture', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of fear in response to God''s presence and judgments. Hebrews reflects Moses'' fear, while Psalms expresses a personal trembling before God''s judgments.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(58, 12, 21, 66, 1, 17, 17, 'I exceedingly fear and quake', 'Fear and Awe in Revelation', 'This connection highlights the theme of fear in the presence of the divine. Both Moses and John experience overwhelming fear, with Moses saying, ''I exceedingly fear and quake,'' and John falling ''at his feet as dead.''', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(58, 12, 21, 27, 10, 17, 17, 'I exceedingly fear and quake', 'Fear and Weakness Before God', 'This connection highlights the overwhelming fear and loss of strength experienced by both Moses and Daniel in the presence of the divine. Both passages emphasize the profound impact of encountering God''s holiness, leading to physical and emotional distress.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(58, 12, 21, 27, 10, 8, 8, 'I exceedingly fear and quake', 'Fear and Weakness in Visions', 'Both passages emphasize a profound sense of fear and loss of strength in the presence of divine visions. Moses expresses his fear and quaking, while Daniel describes losing all strength and feeling corrupted. This connection highlights the overwhelming nature of encountering the divine.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(58, 12, 22, 48, 4, 26, 26, 'the heavenly Jerusalem', 'Connection of Heavenly Jerusalem', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of a heavenly Jerusalem. Hebrews refers to it as the ''heavenly Jerusalem,'' while Galatians describes it as ''Jerusalem which is above.'' This connection highlights the significance of the spiritual city in Christian belief.', 'theme', 0.377, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(58, 12, 22, 50, 3, 20, 20, 'heavenly Jerusalem', 'Connection of Heavenly Citizenship', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of a heavenly realm. Hebrews speaks of the ''heavenly Jerusalem,'' while Philippians refers to our ''conversation'' being in heaven, indicating a shared focus on the believer''s connection to the divine.', 'theme', 0.377, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(58, 12, 22, 19, 48, 2, 2, 'mount Sion', 'Connection Between Mount Zion Passages', 'Both passages emphasize Mount Zion as a significant city. Hebrews refers to it as the heavenly Jerusalem, while Psalms describes it as the city of the great King.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(58, 12, 22, 66, 14, 1, 1, 'mount Sion', 'Connection of Mount Sion', 'Both passages emphasize ''mount Sion'' as a significant location. Hebrews presents it as part of the heavenly Jerusalem, while Revelation depicts the Lamb standing there with the 144,000.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(58, 12, 22, 23, 51, 11, 11, 'mount Sion', 'Connection of Zion and Joy', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of Zion as a place of joy and redemption. Hebrews 12:22 refers to ''mount Sion'' while Isaiah 51:11 speaks of the redeemed returning to Zion with ''everlasting joy.''', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(58, 12, 22, 66, 21, 2, 2, 'the heavenly Jerusalem', 'Connection of Heavenly Jerusalem', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of a heavenly Jerusalem. Hebrews refers to ''mount Sion'' and ''the city of the living God,'' while Revelation describes the ''new Jerusalem'' coming from heaven.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(58, 12, 22, 29, 2, 32, 32, NULL, 'Connection of Mount Zion', 'Both passages emphasize ''mount Zion'' as a significant location for deliverance and divine presence. Hebrews refers to the heavenly Jerusalem, linking it to the deliverance promised in Joel.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(58, 12, 23, 59, 1, 18, 18, 'firstborn', 'Connection of Firstborn and Firstfruits', 'This connection highlights the concept of ''firstborn'' in Hebrews 12:23 and ''firstfruits'' in James 1:18, both indicating a special status among God''s people. Both passages emphasize the idea of being set apart for God''s purpose.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(58, 12, 23, 58, 11, 40, 40, 'made perfect', 'Connection of Perfection in Faith', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of being made perfect. Hebrews 12:23 mentions ''spirits of just men made perfect,'' while Hebrews 11:40 states that ''they without us should not be made perfect.'' This connection highlights the communal aspect of perfection in faith.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(58, 12, 23, 42, 10, 20, 20, 'written in heaven', 'Names Written in Heaven', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of names being written in heaven, highlighting the assurance of belonging to God. Hebrews 12:23 speaks of those written in heaven, while Luke 10:20 directly mentions names written in heaven.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(58, 12, 23, 1, 18, 25, 25, 'Judge of all', 'Judgment and Righteousness Connection', 'Both passages emphasize God''s role as the Judge of all, highlighting the importance of justice and the distinction between the righteous and the wicked. This connection underscores the expectation that God will act justly in His judgments.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(58, 12, 23, 2, 4, 22, 22, 'firstborn', 'Connection of Firstborn Themes', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of ''firstborn.'' Hebrews refers to the ''firstborn'' in a spiritual context, while Exodus identifies Israel as God''s ''firstborn'' son, highlighting a significant relationship between God and His chosen people.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(58, 12, 23, 66, 14, 4, 4, 'firstborn', 'Connection of Firstborn and Virgins', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of being ''firstborn'' and ''firstfruits,'' highlighting a special status among believers. The ''firstborn'' in Hebrews refers to those written in heaven, while Revelation describes the redeemed as ''firstfruits'' unto God.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(58, 12, 23, 19, 94, 2, 2, 'Judge of all', 'Judgment and Justice Themes', 'Both passages emphasize God''s role as a judge. Hebrews 12:23 refers to God as ''the Judge of all,'' while Psalms 94:2 calls upon God to ''render a reward'' as the judge of the earth, highlighting the theme of divine justice.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(58, 12, 24, 58, 9, 15, 15, 'mediator of the new covenant', 'Connection of New Covenant Mediator', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus as the mediator of the new covenant, highlighting his role in redemption. The mention of ''mediator'' in both verses connects their themes of salvation and inheritance.', 'theme', 0.475, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(58, 12, 24, 58, 11, 28, 28, 'the blood of sprinkling', 'Connection of Blood Sprinkling', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of ''sprinkling of blood'' as a means of protection and covenant. Hebrews 12:24 refers to the blood of Jesus, while Hebrews 11:28 discusses the blood used during the Passover.', 'theme', 0.40499999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(58, 12, 24, 1, 4, 10, 10, 'the blood of sprinkling', 'Connection of Blood and Justice', 'This connection highlights the theme of blood as a voice for justice. In Genesis, Abel''s blood cries out, while in Hebrews, Jesus'' blood speaks better things, suggesting a contrast between the cries of vengeance and the redemptive nature of Christ''s sacrifice.', 'theme', 0.391, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(58, 12, 24, 40, 23, 35, 35, 'blood of sprinkling', 'Connection of Righteous Blood', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of bloodshed, specifically referencing Abel''s blood as significant. Hebrews contrasts Abel''s blood with Jesus'' blood, which speaks better things, while Matthew highlights the righteous blood from Abel to Zacharias.', 'theme', 0.391, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(58, 12, 24, 40, 26, 28, 28, NULL, 'Connection of Jesus'' Blood', 'Both passages emphasize the significance of Jesus'' blood in establishing a new covenant. Hebrews 12:24 refers to the blood of sprinkling, while Matthew 26:28 explicitly mentions the blood of the new testament, linking them thematically.', 'theme', 0.391, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(58, 12, 24, 54, 2, 5, 5, 'mediator of the new covenant', 'Mediation of Christ', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus as the mediator between God and humanity. Hebrews highlights His role in the new covenant, while 1 Timothy affirms His unique position as the mediator for all men.', 'theme', 0.391, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(58, 12, 24, 2, 24, 8, 8, NULL, 'Connection of Covenant Blood', 'Both passages emphasize the significance of blood in establishing a covenant. Hebrews refers to Jesus'' blood as speaking better things, while Exodus highlights the blood sprinkled on the people as part of the covenant.', 'theme', 0.377, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(58, 12, 25, 58, 8, 5, 5, 'him that speaketh from heaven', 'Heavenly Communication and Obedience', 'This connection highlights the importance of heeding divine instruction. Both passages emphasize the necessity of following God''s commands, whether spoken from heaven or as exemplified in the earthly tabernacle''s design.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(58, 12, 25, 5, 30, 17, 17, 'turn away from him that speaketh', 'Warning Against Turning Away', 'Both passages emphasize the danger of turning away from God and not listening to His voice. Hebrews warns against refusing Him who speaks from heaven, while Deuteronomy cautions against a heart that turns away and does not hear.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(58, 12, 25, 58, 2, 1, 3, 'refuse not him that speaketh', 'Warning Against Neglecting Salvation', 'Both passages emphasize the seriousness of heeding divine communication. Hebrews 12:25 warns against refusing the one who speaks from heaven, while Hebrews 2:3 questions how one can escape neglecting such great salvation. This connection highlights the urgency of responding to God''s message.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(58, 12, 25, 2, 20, 22, 22, 'speaketh from heaven', 'Divine Communication from Heaven', 'This connection highlights the theme of God speaking from heaven. Both passages emphasize the importance of heeding God''s voice, whether it is from heaven or on earth.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(58, 12, 25, 20, 13, 18, 18, 'refuse not him that speaketh', 'Instruction and Refusal', 'This connection highlights the consequences of refusing instruction. Both passages emphasize the importance of heeding the voice that speaks, whether from heaven or through reproof, suggesting that ignoring such guidance leads to negative outcomes.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(58, 12, 25, 38, 7, 11, 11, 'refuse not him that speaketh', 'Refusal to Listen', 'Both passages emphasize the act of refusing to listen to divine communication. Hebrews warns against rejecting the one who speaks from heaven, while Zechariah describes a refusal to hearken and an active stopping of ears.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(58, 12, 25, 2, 16, 29, 29, 'him that speaketh', 'Divine Communication and Obedience', 'This connection highlights the importance of heeding divine instructions. Both passages emphasize the necessity of responding to God''s commands, whether through the voice from heaven or the provision of the Sabbath.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(58, 12, 26, 37, 2, 6, 7, 'Yet once more I shake not the earth only, but also heaven', 'Divine Shaking of Creation', 'Both passages emphasize a divine promise to shake the heavens and the earth. Hebrews references this shaking as a fulfillment of God''s earlier declaration in Haggai, indicating a continuity in God''s actions across both texts.', 'theme', 0.475, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
